    uprightMeaning: "The Five of Wands shows five figures in a chaotic scuffle, each wielding a wand but none landing a decisive blow. This is the card of competition, creative tension, and the friction that arises when multiple perspectives or ambitions collide. Unlike the devastating conflict of the Swords suit, the Wands conflict is more akin to a spirited debate — heated but not destructive. This card often appears during brainstorming sessions, competitive environments, or situations where egos are jostling for position. The challenge is to channel this combative energy productively rather than letting it devolve into chaos.",
    reversedMeaning: "Reversed, the Five of Wands suggests the conflict is resolving, or you are choosing to avoid confrontation. Competition may be easing, or you may be finding ways to collaborate rather than compete. Alternatively, the conflict has turned inward — you may be battling yourself rather than external opponents.",
    loveMeaning: "In love, the Five of Wands indicates petty arguments, competition for attention, or the kind of friction that arises when two passionate people disagree. This is not a relationship-ending conflict — it is the healthy tension that, if handled maturely, can actually deepen understanding.",
    careerMeaning: "The Five of Wands signals workplace competition, office politics, or the creative tension of a team with strong opinions. Stand your ground but remain open to others' ideas. The best outcomes emerge when diverse perspectives are synthesized rather than silenced.",
    yesOrNo: "No",
    advice: "Engage the conflict rather than running from it. The Five of Wands reminds you that friction creates fire — and fire creates transformation. Channel the competitive energy toward a constructive outcome rather than letting it scatter into chaos.",
